t www.luminosoa.org to learn more. This book provides the first overview of the history and development of Islam in Afghanistan. Written by leading international experts, chapters cover every era from the conversion of Afghanistan through the medieval period to the present day. Based on primary sources in Arabic, Persian, Pashto, Uzbek, and Urdu, its depth of coverage is unrivalled in providing a developmental picture of Afghanistan's Islam, including such issues as the rise of Sufism, women's religiosity, state religious policies, and transnational Islamism. Looking beyond the unifying rhetoric of theology, the book reveals the disparate and contested forms of Afghanistan's Islam.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIslamxHistoryzAfghanistan. 0aIslamzAfghanistanxHistory. 0aMuslimsxHistoryzAfghanistan. 0aMuslimszAfghanistanxHistory. 7aRELIGION / Islam / General.2bisacsh1 aAhsan, Sonia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArbabzadah, Nushin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAzad, Arezou, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaldauf, Ingeborg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBezhan, Faridullah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuchs, Simon Wolfgang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, Nile, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, Nile, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHaroon, Sana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcChesney, R. D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul